sentence: Analysts at Bank of America/Merrill Lynch on Tuesday offered some further positive commentary on home improvement warehouse operators The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ) and Lowe's Companies, Inc. ( LOW ).
The firm said it boosted its estimates on HD through 2013 while lifting its price target to $50.
That new target suggests a 9% upside to the stock's Monday closing price of $45.93.
Bank of America/Merrill Lynch noted the company is well-leveraged to higher building renovation demand.
Similarly, the firm also boosted its estimates and price target for HD competitor LOW.
The analyst now expects LOW shares to reach $29, which implies a 6% upside.
Bank of America/Merrill Lynch said Lowe's is cutting costs and could see higher demand in coming quarters.
Home Depot and Lowe's shares both posted small losses in premarket trading Tuesday.
Shares of Home Depot ( HD ) have a 2.53% dividend yield, based on last night's closing stock price of $45.93.
The stock has technical support in the $40-$42 price area.
If the shares can firm up, we see overhead resistance around the $50 price level.
Shares of Lowe's ( LOW ) have a 2.04% dividend yield, based on last night's closing stock price of $27.39.
The stock has technical support in the $24-$25 price area.
If the shares can firm up, we see overhead resistance around the $30 price level.
The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ) and Lowe's Companies, Inc. ( LOW ) and both currently rated "Neutral" by Dividend.com.
